Linked Lists

A linked list is a data structure where each element is a separate object.

Each object is called a node. Each node contains two things:

  • The data

    The data

  • A reference to the next node

    A reference to the next node

The linked list starts at the head. If a node points to null, it indicates the end of the linked list.

You can build your own linked list by creating node objects, but in this lesson, youll be using the built-in Java linked lists.

Arrays are quicker at accessing objects, but linked lists are quicker at inserting and deleting objects.

Linked Lists Methods

After creating a linked list, you can use the built-in linked list methods.

  •  add(index, element) : inserts element into the index position

     add(index, element) : inserts element into the index position

  •  remove(index) : removes the element at the index position

     remove(index) : removes the element at the index position

  •  contains(element) : returns true if the list contains the element

     contains(element) : returns true if the list contains the element

  •  get(index) : returns element at the index position

     get(index) : returns element at the index position

  •  set(index, value) : replaces the element at the index position with the value

     set(index, value) : replaces the element at the index position with the value

To read more about the built in linked list methods, check out this link.

What method would you use if you wanted to add an element to the end of a list?

You're tasked with creating a  dynamic student roster.

Create a linked list for the student roster.

Implementation

  • To create a linked list in Java, create a new class called "LinkedList" in the DataStructures project.

Create a class named "LinkedLists":

  1. Right-click the src folder.
  2. New > Class.
  3. Type "LinkedLists".
  4. Inside your LinkedLists class, type "psvm" and press Tab to create the main method.
  5. Click Finish.

From there, import the Linked List class.

  • 1

    Above the class declaration, import in the LinkedList class:
     import java.util.LinkedList; 

    Above the class declaration, import in the LinkedList class:
     import java.util.LinkedList; 

Then there are two steps for creating and using a linked list:

  • 2

    Inside the main method, create a linked list object. For this assignment, the list is called students:
     LinkedList<String> students = new LinkedList<String>(); 

    Inside the main method, create a linked list object. For this assignment, the list is called students:

    After creating a new linked list object, add and edit the elements inside using the built-in methods.

Dot Notation

If you want to access a field or call a method from an instance of a class, write a dot (.) after the name of the class to see all the options, i.e.   students.add(index, element); .

Building the Code

Advantages and Disadvantages

Advantages

  • Linked lists are quick at inserting and deleting objects. 
  • The size grows and shrinks as needed.

Disadvantages

  • A linked list is slower at finding objects. It doesnt allow you to directly access an element. Items are accessed from the beginning of the list.

When to Use a Linked List?

  • Youll be inserting and deleting many objects.

    Youll be inserting and deleting many objects.

  • You dont need to randomly access a specific element.

    You dont need to randomly access a specific element.

  • Youre not sure how many items there will be.

    Youre not sure how many items there will be.

Recap

  • Linked lists contain two parts: the data and the address to the next node.
  • If a node points to 0 its the end of the list.
  • Linked lists are great for inserting and deleting objects, but bad at randomly accessing an element.
